===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}

{{Han compound|日|月|ls=ic|t1=sun|t2=moon}} – the sun just rising and the moon not yet set – dawn ({{l|zh|天明}}). Alternatively, it may be interpreted as two bright celestial bodies – bright. This form was already found in the oracle bone script and was prevalent throughout the eras.

Three other forms were found in the oracle bone script:
* {{l|zh|朙}} < {{Han compound|囧|月|t1=window}} – the moon shining through a window – moonlight. This form was also prevalent in the ancient scripts and was considered to be the standard form in ''{{w|Shuowen}}''. See this form's entry for its historical forms.
* {{l|zh|眀}} < {{Han compound|目|月|t1=eye}} – bright eyes. This form was rarely attested, so it is still uncertain whether this form is actually equivalent to {{lang|zh|明}}. It reappeared in the bamboo script of the {{w|Qin dynasty}}, but this was probably a corruption of {{l|zh|朙}}.
* {{l|zh|𤰾}} < {{Han compound|田|月}} – probably a corruption of the above forms.

===Etymology 1===
Of either {{inh|zh|sit-pro|-}} origin, compare
* {{cog|bo|མདངས||facial color, appearance, brightness}} ({{zh-ref|Bodman, 1980}}), or
* {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*brwaŋ||loud; bright}} (STEDT); making it cognate with {{cog|my|ပြင်း||acute; violent}}, {{cog|my|ပြောင်||to shine}}.
Or from {{der|zh|aav}}, cognate with {{och-l|亮|gloss=bright}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). For more see {{och-l|亮}}.

{{och-l|盟|gloss=covenant}} is a derivative ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

